\f3\fs20 \cf0  Larry Hogan, a Republican, is governor of Maryland. Ralph Northam, a Democrat, is governor of Virginia. They are members of the U.S. 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  Alliance. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The Trump administration's pursuit of policies to reverse or supplant environmental laws that reduce greenhouse-gas emissions has made combating 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  difficult. But where the federal government refuses to lead, state governments will.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 For the sake of our future and the future of our children, it is time to put aside partisan interest and get to work.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Today,  nations from around the world are in Poland working on a common set of rules that will govern the implementation of the Paris 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  agreement  and report on their progress. The citizens of Maryland and Virginia, as well as all those in other states across the country, have a stake in ensuring that the agreement succeeds. The difference between continuing to emit carbon at current levels and limiting global warming to 1.5 degrees Celsius (2.7 degrees Fahrenheit), as a recent U.N. report on 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  recommended, is millions of lives and billions of dollars.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 That is why we support the elected officials and leaders from cities, tribes, businesses, universities, hospitals and churches who represent U.S. support for the Paris 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  agreement. Together, this delegation of leaders will make it clear to the world that we are doing our part to keep the United States on track to fulfill the promise it made in Paris.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 We are already experiencing the negative impacts of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , as the recent National 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  Assessment from 13 federal agencies made painfully clear. The impacts differ by location, but whether it's stronger storms and rising seas, or hotter heat waves and more intense wildfires, every state is grappling with the effects of a warming 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone . This new report from the federal government confirms what we already know: 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  can hurt public health and cripple our economy.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Our most important job as governors is ensuring the safety of our constituents. So when we face a threat to people's livelihood and way of life, showing leadership means acknowledging the risk and addressing it. 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  hits Democrats and Republicans alike, and we need to work together, despite our differences, to stop it.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 This is why a bipartisan group of governors joined to form the U.S. 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  Alliance. After starting with three governors,  the alliance has now grown to 17 state leaders who have committed to reducing greenhouse-gas emissions consistent with the goals of the Paris agreement. We are united in our belief that smart, coordinated state action can ensure that the United States continues to contribute to the global effort to address 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone . Together, we are taking action to implement a range of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  policies - such as lowering the cost of renewable energy and promoting the use of electric vehicles.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In our home states of Maryland and Virginia, we are experiencing rising seas, more extreme weather events, regular high-tide flooding and a 
\f1\i\b \ul changing
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  Chesapeake Bay. That's why Maryland has become a leader in the Regional Greenhouse Gas Initiative and passed a law to reduce greenhouse-gas emissions by 40 percent,  creating a model for others to follow. Maryland also has an active, bipartisan Commission on 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate Change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone   and is a leader in 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  resilience and preparedness, as well as championing green infrastructure, open space, and a 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  academy for local officials and citizens. Recently, the state has announced its intention to ban the manufacture and use of hydrofluorocarbons, a super-polluting greenhouse gas.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 And just to the south, Virginia has begun the process to reduce carbon pollution from power plants by 30 percent by 2030 and recently announced its intention to significantly reduce emissions of methane - a greenhouse gas that is more than 80 times  more damaging than carbon dioxide in the short term. Virginia also issued an executive order last month detailing steps to address extreme weather, including the creation of a Coastal Resilience Master Plan to protect private property and critical public assets, using nature-based infrastructure whenever possible.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Our states will continue to develop our clean- and renewable-energy supplies. We will reduce emissions from fossil fuels. And we will make plans to adapt and protect our citizens and our coastlines. These steps will help slow 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , but we need help. We call on leaders of all political persuasions to get to work and cooperate across aisles and across borders - both national and international - to meet the challenge of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone .
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Larry Hogan, a Republican, is governor of Maryland. Ralph Northam, a Democrat, is governor of Virginia. They are members of the U.S. 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  Alliance.
