\f3\fs20 \cf0 A pair of polls published Tuesday found broad recognition among Americans that the world is getting warmer after they endured a year of intense wildfires and devastating hurricanes.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Taken together, both polls - one from researchers at Yale and George Mason universities and the other from those at the University of Chicago and the Associated Press - depict citizens who increasingly see the conspicuous effects of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  around them and take the issue more personally than ever.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 An overwhelming majority of the U.S. public - more than 7 in 10 American adults -acknowledge that the world is getting warmer, according to the two surveys, which were both conducted late last year and published independently on Tuesday.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "It was a completely crazy fluke that they came out today," said Sam Ori, executive director of the Energy Policy Institute at the University of Chicago, which participated in one of the surveys.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The percentage of Americans who say the 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is 
\f1\i\b \ul changing
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  has steadily increased since 2015, the Yale-George Mason team has found. But it is the number of Americans who say the issue is personally important to them that spiked sharply last year.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 A record-high total of 72 percent of U.S. adults polled between Nov. 28 and Dec. 11 by the Yale and George Mason team regard 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  as personally important - up 16 percentage points since March 2015 and 9 points since March 2018. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "I think we're witnessing a sea 
\f1\i\b \ul change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  in public understanding of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone ," said Ed Maibach, director of George Mason's Center for 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate Change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  Communication.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The 
\f1\i\b \ul change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  may be happening because Americans increasingly see 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  as affecting them (49 percent) or their families (56 percent) or their countrymen (65 percent).
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 There are at least three broad factors that may be behind that recent uptick, Maibach said. One is the alarm bells recently rung by top scientists working for the U.S. government and United Nations. Major scientific reports from them indicate that the damage from 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is intensifying across the country and that the world has little more than a decade to curb 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone -altering emissions and hold warming to 1.5 degrees Celsius. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Another possible factor: Efforts made by President Trump's administration to undo steps to reduce greenhouse gas pollution - the chief factor in 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  according to scientists. The unraveling of such regulations runs counter to those scientific findings but may be raising awareness of the issue.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 A third, and perhaps most important, reason is the spate of nasty weather events in recent years, which include the sort of massive wildfires in the Western United States and intense hurricanes in the Atlantic that many 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  scientists expect to become more common in a warming world. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "2018 was the year from hell in terms of extreme weather events and the number of Americans harmed by them," Maibach said.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Lending credence to that notion is the other poll, from the University of Chicago and the Associated Press-NORC Center for Public Affairs Research. Among the respondents to that survey who said they found the science of man-made 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  more convincing than they did five years ago, three-quarters said recent hurricanes, floods, droughts and unusual heat influenced their views.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "The biggest driver by a wide margin is the extreme weather over the last several months," Ori said. "The wildfires in California were actually ongoing during the period when the poll was taken," in mid-November.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But that survey, like others, identified the typical cleavages on the issue along party lines that historically have made passing 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  legislation difficult. Eighty-six percent of self-identified Democrats said they recognize 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is happening, compared with 70 percent of independents and 52 percent of Republicans.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 That greater concern about 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  identified in both surveys is a return to the past. In November 2008, when Barack Obama was first elected to the White House, 70 percent of Americans said the issue of global warming was personally important to them.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 It was only when Democrats tried to pass cap-and-trade legislation aimed at addressing greenhouse gas emissions that the concern plummeted by 14 points by 2010.
\f0\fs24 \
