\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Now that they have control of the House, Democrats have used their newfound power to pack the calendar in Congress with hearings on what they see as the biggest environmental crisis facing the nation and the world.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In the first 64 days of the new Congress, various congressional committees have scheduled at least 15 hearings explicitly on the causes and effects of - and potential response to - the world's warming 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone .
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Democrats want to elevate an issue that they say House Republicans almost entirely ignored during their eight years in power in the chamber.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "Today's hearing on 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is long overdue," House Energy and Commerce Committee Chairman Frank Pallone Jr. (D-N.J.) said during his panel's first hearing in the new Congress in early February. "We are feeling its effects now, and the influence of unchecked 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is becoming more obvious every year."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Democrats sought to cast February as the month in which they would put a focus on 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , though the hearings are stretching into March. Most of the time, the meetings were not convened to discuss any particular piece of legislation. They also didn't tackle the nonbinding Green New Deal resolution that has captured the attention of Washington.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 They served instead as an opportunity for members to gather testimony from 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  experts - and to stump about the urgency needed to address global warming.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 One hearing in the House Natural Resources Committee sought to examine how 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone -fueled floods and wildfires are disrupting Native American communities. Another in the House Transportation and Infrastructure Committee looked at how emissions from cars, airplanes and other modes of transportation makes global warming worse.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Showing how deep into the weeds Democrats want to dive, the most recent of those 15 hearings, in the Energy and Commerce Committee on Thursday, focused on rules that would increase the energy efficiency of lightbulbs and other devices.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 And Democrats are far from done. House Speaker Nancy Pelosi reinstituted a special select committee on 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  that was disbanded by Republicans when they were in the majority. It has yet to meet, but that panel, chaired by Rep. Kathy Castor (D-Fla.), will collect facts about 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  from scientists and experts rather than focus on crafting legislation.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "We're facing the crisis of our generation," Castor said at one of the other several 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  hearings on the Hill in February. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Even one Republican chairwoman on the side of the Capitol still controlled by the GOP - Sen. Lisa Murkowski of Alaska - has joined in the hearing frenzy, convening one this week on advancing new technologies to reduce greenhouse gas emissions from the electricity sector.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Like much of the rest of the Arctic, her state has warmed twice as fast as the Lower 48 states, a fact she noted during her opening remarks. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "This has got to be a priority for all of us," Murkowski said. "Certainly in Alaska we view that there is no choice here."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 During their eight years in power in the House, Republicans largely declined to directly shine a spotlight on 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone . 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Energy and Commerce Committee Republicans say the committee addressed 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  in the last GOP-led Congress through hearings focused on boosting renewable and nuclear energy and promoting energy efficiency.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But on other committees, Republicans often criticized 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  scientists themselves - as then-House Science Committee Chair Lamar Smith (R-Tex.) did when he probed a group of National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration researchers.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But some top GOP lawmakers are responding to the new political reality in Washington by calling for action on 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  - as long as it is bipartisan.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 At times, their remarks even got personal.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Rep. Greg Walden, the ranking Republican on the Energy and Commerce panel, held up a jar of ash during one hearing to illustrate the devastation of wildfires in his eastern Oregon district. And the new top Republican on the science panel, Rep. Frank D. Lucas (R-Okla.), cited his experience as a farmer during another hearing as he called for more investment in carbon capture and nuclear energy technologies.
