\f3\fs20 \cf0 It is not just about the Earth's rising temperatures. Many Democrats running for president see 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  as symptomatic of another problem: too much money in politics. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 One White House hopeful, Sen. Michael F. Bennet (D-Colo.), on Thursday unveiled an anticorruption plan explicitly meant to make it easier for Congress to address global warming - and other Democratic priorities. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "So much of what we've got to get done, from 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  to health care to 
\f1\i\b \ul changing
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  [the] tax code, is going to require us to 
\f1\i\b \ul change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  the way our politics work. Because for the decade that I've been in the Senate, it largely hasn't worked," Bennet told reporters.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 He's just one of many 2020 candidates tying desired legislative action on 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  with the need to overhaul how money is spent on electoral campaigns and lobbying. Their thinking goes: As the oil, gas and coal industries pump money into political campaigns, fossil-fuel interests have been able to forestall meaningful legislation to slow 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone .
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Montana Gov. Steve Bullock (D) is, similarly, putting campaign finance reform at the center of his presidential bid in part to address the rising temperatures contributing to wildfires in his home state. "Tackling money in politics is the first step towards addressing 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , skyrocketing healthcare costs, income inequality - and all of the biggest crises of our time," Bullock tweeted shortly after announcing his candidacy.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 And in interviews, speeches and social media posts, Sens. Kirsten Gillibrand (N.Y.), Kamala D. Harris (Calif.) and Bernie Sanders (I-Vt.), as well as former congressman Beto O'Rourke of Texas and Pete Buttigieg, the mayor of South Bend, Ind., have also lamented the big role rich donors are playing in politics and how that is forestalling action on 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone .
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "You want a government that's going to be responsive on 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  fast?" yet another Democratic candidate, Sen. Elizabeth Warren of Massachusetts, said at the "We the People Summit" summit in April. "Not so long as the oil industry is calling the shots in this town."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Democratic candidates are paying attention to the issue partly because of the swarms of activists who have shown up at campaign events and pressed hopefuls, such as O'Rourke and former vice president Joe Biden, to commit to refuse campaign donations from lobbyists or executives in the oil, gas or coal business.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 So far, the pressure has worked. The vast majority of the 2020 Democratic field - 18 of the 23 candidates, including O'Rourke - has signed the "No Fossil Fuel Money pledge," according to the anti-fossil-fuel nonprofit advocacy group Oil 
\f1\i\b \ul Change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  US. Biden is expected to sign the pledge in the coming days.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Bennet's plan in particular calls for a lifetime ban on lobbying for former members of Congress, a crackdown on coordination between candidates and ostensibly independent "super PACs" and a constitutional amendment to overturn what many Democrats see as the biggest step back in campaign finance reform in a generation - the  Citizens United  Supreme Court decision.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Citing the Constitution's First Amendment guarantee of free speech, the high court in 2010 ruled to bar the federal government from limiting political spending of corporations and labor unions via groups independent of campaigns. Ever since, many Democrats say, "dark money" groups have uncorked a spigot of political spending.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "John McCain ran on 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone ," Bennet said of the 2008 GOP presidential nominee. "He raised it over and over again himself during the debates. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "What happened? What 
\f1\i\b \ul changed
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone ? It was the decision in 2010 in  Citizens United  which opened the floodgates of the Koch brothers' money and corrupted our politics," he continued, referring to political spending from billionaire industrialists Charles and David Koch.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Energy firms in particular are spending big money on politics. According to End Citizens United, a political action committee that opposes the Supreme Court decision, oil and gas companies accounted for 10 of the 17 largest corporate contributions to outside groups during the 2018 elections.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The  Citizens United  decision, according to its opponents, has had a measurable effect on how willing Republicans are to support 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  legislation now that fossil-fuel companies, many of which oppose strict carbon-pollution rules, have more leverage over lawmakers.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "The fossil-fuel industry snuffed out Senate bipartisanship on 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone ," Sen. Sheldon Whitehouse (D-R.I.) said this week at the National Press Club. "Weaponization of that new unlimited dark money powered by the fossil-fuel industry cost us a decade of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  progress."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Few members of Congress have harped on this message longer than Whitehouse. He is not running for president, but he urged 2020 candidates to pick up his argument.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "Any Democrat is going to be buoyed by the public pressure on this," he said.
