\f3\fs20 \cf0 Official defends editsto website while criticscall them 'cleansing'
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 A unit of the National Institutes of Health has removed references to 
\f1\i\b \ul climate "change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone " from its website, deletions that one environmental group criticizes as "cleansing" but that an NIH official described as minor.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The revisions occurred on the site of the National Institute of Environmental Health Sciences (NIEHS).
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 A headline that read "
\f1\i\b \ul Climate Change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  and Human Health," for example, was altered to "
\f1\i\b \ul Climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  and Human Health." A menu title that read "
\f1\i\b \ul Climate Change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  and Children's Health" in June now appears as "
\f1\i\b \ul Climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  and Children's Health." Links to a fact sheet on "
\f1\i\b \ul Climate Change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  and Human Health" also were removed.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "The cleansing continues," said David Doniger, director of the 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  and clean-air program at the Natural Resources Defense Council. "But they're not going to be able to erase the science, or the truth, by scrubbing websites."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  were revealed in a report by the Environmental Data and Governance Initiative, a group of nonprofits and academics that monitor what they call "potential threats" to federal policy and scientific research on energy and the environment.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But Christine Flowers, the NIEHS director of communications, played down the 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  Wednesday. She said she made them as she added and moved information on the site over a period of months.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "It's a minor 
\f1\i\b \ul change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  to a title page," Flowers said of one headline alteration, "but the information we provide remains the same. In fact, it's been expanded."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The phrase "
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone " still can be found several times in the text below the headline that now reads "
\f1\i\b \ul Climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  and Human Health." Also still available is a "
\f1\i\b \ul Climate Change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  and Human Health Literature Portal."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Similar word 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  have been made on Interior Department, Transportation Department and Environmental Protection Agency website pages that mentioned 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone . Scientists inside and outside the government have questioned the motivations because of top Trump administration officials' doubts about how much human activity influences global warming.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In some cases, though, career staffers may have been responsible for the new wording on sites in an effort to avoid administration scrutiny on hot-button issues.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The EPA's "
\f1\i\b \ul Climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  Ready Water Utilities" site was renamed before Donald Trump took office - to "Creating Resilient Water Utilities."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In April, the EPA took down several website pages that contained detailed 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  data and scientific information. That action, on the eve of a large demonstration in Washington about protecting the environment, included removal of a Web page explaining 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  that had been on the site for nearly two decades.
\f0\fs24 \

