\f3\fs20 \cf0 Scientists project average temperature rise of 4.1 to 8.1 degrees if trends hold
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The current pace of human-caused carbon emissions is increasingly likely to trigger irreversible damage to the planet, according to a comprehensive international study released Wednesday.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20  Researchers studying one of the most important and vexing topics in 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  science - how the Earth's 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  will respond to a doubling of the amount of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere - found that warming is extremely unlikely to be on the low end of estimates.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Scientists now say that if human activities, such as burning oil, gas and coal,  as well as deforestation, continue apace, the Earth's global average temperature will most likely increase between 4.1 and 8.1 degrees Fahrenheit (2.3 and 4.5 degrees Celsius) by about 2070. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 If warming reaches even just the midpoint of this new range, it would be extremely damaging, said Kate Marvel, a physicist at NASA's Goddard Institute of Space Studies and Columbia University, who called it the equivalent of a "five-alarm fire" for the planet.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Researchers have long believed that a doubling of carbon dioxide would increase temperatures between 2.7 and 8.1 degrees Fahrenheit (1.5 and 4.5 Celsius), as first laid out in a 1979 report.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The new range published Wednesday shows at least a 95 percent chance that a doubling of carbon dioxide, which the world is on course to reach within the next 50 years, would result in warming greater than 3.6 degrees Fahrenheit (2 degrees Celsius) relative to preindustrial temperatures.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 That's significant because 3.6 degrees Fahrenheit  is the threshold beyond which scientists say the Earth will suffer catastrophic effects - disruptive sea level rise, intolerable heat waves and other extreme weather and permanent damage to ecosystems.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Staying below that is still possible. If emissions are drastically cut in the near term, a doubling of carbon dioxide levels could be avoided.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The study by 25 researchers from around the world and published in the journal Reviews of Geophysics is the result of a four-year effort sponsored by the World 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  Research Program. 
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs20 \cf0 A scientific 'holy grail'
\f0\b0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb200\qj\partightenfactor0

\f3\fs20 \cf0 For decades, 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  scientists have been seeking to  answer the question of how much global temperatures would climb if the amount of carbon dioxide in the Earth's atmosphere were to double. This measure was estimated in a 1979 study from the National Research Council led by Massachusetts Institute of Technology professor Jules Charney.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The "Charney Report" concluded that the planet's 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  sensitivity was most likely within the range of 2.6 to 8.1 degrees Fahrenheit (1.5 to 4.5 Celsius).
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Ever since, researchers have tried to narrow that range, contending with myriad uncertainties in how the oceans and atmosphere respond to historical 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  in solar output, the planet's orbit, past periods with higher amounts of carbon dioxide in the air as well as feedback such as how various cloud types trap or reflect heat energy. In addition, scientists have wrestled with uncertainties in models that simulate past, present and future 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone .
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "Constraining 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  sensitivity has been something of a holy grail in 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  science for some time," said study co-author Zeke Hausfather, director of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  and energy at the Breakthrough Institute.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  sensitivity question has taken on new urgency as some of the newest computer models developed for the U.N. Intergovernmental Panel on 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate Change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  (IPCC), due in a report  next year, show the Earth is more responsive to carbon dioxide than depicted in earlier models. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The new result narrows the range from what Charney and his colleagues calculated while raising the lower bound.
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs20 \cf0 Multiple lines of evidence
\f0\b0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb200\qj\partightenfactor0

\f3\fs20 \cf0 To produce the study, teams of researchers worked like   detectives, sifting  through multiple sources of evidence. Some of the data examined include instrument records since the industrial revolution, paleoclimate records from coral reefs and ice cores that provide evidence of prehistoric temperatures, and satellite observations and intricate models of how the 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  system works.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 To reach their new authoritative estimates, the researchers required that multiple lines of evidence point to the same general conclusion and that this be explained without being the result of a bias that influences one or more sources of evidence.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "An important part of the process was to ensure that the lines of evidence were more or less independent," lead author Steven Sherwood, a 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  scientist at the University of New South Wales's ARC Center of Excellence for 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  Extremes, said in a news release. "You can think of it as the mathematical version of trying to determine if a rumor you hear separately from two people could have sprung from the same source; or if one of two eyewitnesses to a crime has been influenced by hearing the story of the other one," Sherwood stated.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Andrew Dessler, a 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  scientist at Texas A&M University who was not involved in the study, called this "a tour de force of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  science." He said via email that the study "really, really kills the skeptical argument that 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  sensitivity is low."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "It would have been great if the skeptics had been correct and 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  sensitivity was, say, 1.5\'c2\'b0C, but that's not the world we live in," Dessler said.
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs20 \cf0 Enabling decision-making
\f0\b0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb200\qj\partightenfactor0

\f3\fs20 \cf0 The term "
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  sensitivity" might seem like an academic construct, a metric that matters more in the grand theories and computer models of scientists than it does in everyday life.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In fact, the study has a message that matters a great deal: There is  little or no chance that warming caused by human  activities turns out to be minor.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 There are at least two main pieces of evidence that lead to the conclusion, according to the study.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20  The first is simply the warming that has already occurred since the industrial revolution. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Currently, with atmospheric concentrations of carbon dioxide at 415 parts per million, compared with a preindustrial level of 280 parts per million, the world is  about halfway toward  doubling atmospheric carbon dioxide.  And already, the Earth has warmed by at least 1 degree Celsius (1.8 degrees Fahrenheit) above  preindustrial temperatures.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 At the same time, researchers rejected the idea that  there is any factor in the 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  system that will counteract the warming trend in a meaningful way.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In the past, 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  contrarians and doubters have suggested that clouds might limit warming by reflecting sunlight  from Earth to cool the planet some. But the study finds that isn't likely to happen.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "We find that a negative total cloud feedback is very unlikely," the authors write.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "The uncertainty is really asymmetric here," Marvel said in an interview. "We can be very confident in ruling out sensitivities on the low end. So basically what we're saying here is that there is really no evidence for any sort of natural response, any sort of big, stabilizing feedback, that in the absence of human actions, is going to save us from 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone ."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But Gavin Schmidt, a study co-author and Marvel's colleague at NASA Goddard, offered some optimism, noting that collective action by nations could prevent the doubling of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "The primary determinant of future 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is human actions," Marvel said.
\f0\fs24 \
