\f3\fs20 \cf0 "Number of House members who voted in 2011 that 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  was a 'hoax': 240."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 - text of a new video by Obama political arm Organizing for Action
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 President Obama's new political group, Organizing for Action, recently released a video that mocks Republican lawmakers for appearing to play down or dismiss concerns about 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone . Some of the clips are fairly interesting or amusing, depending on your perspective. It has already been viewed more than 235,000 times on YouTube. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 We've written before about the growing consensus among 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  researchers that 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is the result of human activity; there's little debate about that among scientists, although surveys show increasing skepticism among the American public. But we were intrigued by the video's claim that 240 House lawmakers had voted to declare 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  to be a "hoax."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Officials at OFA did not respond to repeated queries about the video, which always makes us especially suspicious. Our colleagues at FactCheck.Org report that the "240" number refers to a vote on an amendment offered by House Democrats, which failed 240 to 184, to a Republican-crafted bill on regulating greenhouse gases. So let's dig into what actually happened. 
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs20 \cf0 The Facts
\f0\b0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb200\qj\partightenfactor0

\f3\fs20 \cf0 The underlying bill, known as the Energy Tax Prevention Act of 2011, was intended to thwart an effort by the Environmental Protection Agency to regulate gases believed to affect 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone . It would have amended the Clean Air Act to prevent the EPA from regulating carbon dioxide, methane and at least five other gases, instead leaving such policy decisions in the hands of Congress.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The bill, which passed the House 255 to 172 but did not advance in the Senate, danced gingerly around the question of whether humans have a role in 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone . 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The bill's language included a "sense of the Congress" that stated that 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  was a problem without giving the reasons: "There is established scientific concern over warming of the 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  system based upon evidence from observations of increases in global average air and ocean temperatures, widespread melting of snow and ice, and rising global average sea level . . . addressing 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is an international issue, involving complex scientific and economic considerations . . . the United States has a role to play in resolving global 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  matters on an international basis."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Nevertheless, at the start of the debate on the bill, Rep. Henry A. Waxman (D-Calif.),  had declared that the premise of the underlying bill "is that 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is a hoax and carbon pollution does not endanger health and welfare." 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The Democratic amendment, offered by Waxman, sought to marry a reference to the EPA with language that reflected the scientific consensus: "Congress accepts the scientific findings of the Environmental Protection Agency that 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is occurring, is caused largely by human activities, and poses significant risks for public health and welfare." The second part of the amendment comes almost straight out of the conclusions of the National Research Council in 2010.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But of course, mentioning the EPA's similar conclusions was also intended as a poison pill in a bill designed to clip the agency's wings. Rep. F. James Sensenbrenner Jr. (R-Wis.) complained that "this is an amendment that attempts to reverse the entire thrust of this legislation."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Sensenbrenner added that "this is not a debate on the underlying science of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone ." 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Another lawmaker who spoke against the amendment, then-Rep. Robert J. Dold (R-Ill.), echoed that: "I believe that human activity is also playing a role. The question is how big a role." 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Waxman's amendment was a classic legislative gambit, goading the other side to reject language that - on its face - appears reasonable. To that extent, even in failure the amendment was a success. The Hill newspaper headlined its article on the vote: "Amendment that says 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is occurring fails in House."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The video then gilds the lily by immediately following a reference to the vote with a clip of a floor speech by Rep. Paul C. Broun (R-Ga.): "The idea of human-induced global 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is one of the greatest hoaxes perpetrated out of the scientific community." But that speech was given in 2009 - not during the debate over the 2011 amendment.  
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Moreover, nowhere in the amendment does the word "hoax" appear. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 As Dold's comments make clear, a vote against the amendment did not mean someone was a 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  denier. Indeed, four GOP lawmakers who voted against the Waxman amendment in 2011, for instance, in 2009 had voted for Waxman's 
\f1\i\b \ul climate-change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  legislation to create a cap-and-trade system to reduce greenhouse gases.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Meanwhile, Republicans were not alone in rejecting the Waxman amendment: Three Democrats voted against it. One, Rep. Nick J. Rahall II (W.Va.), was quoted in 2010 as saying "we can't put our heads under the blanket and pretend 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  doesn't exist."
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs20 \cf0 The Pinocchio Test
\f0\b0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb200\qj\partightenfactor0

\f3\fs20 \cf0 Readers should always be skeptical when political ads attach a particular meaning to a congressional vote. In this case, the Obama group has twisted the meaning of a relatively minor amendment, which was clearly intended to become fodder for future campaign ads.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 There's little evidence that a vote against this amendment meant that a lawmaker was affirming that "
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  was a hoax." There are clearly lawmakers who voted against the amendment who believe that human activity contributes in some way to 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  - and the underlying bill states that there is "established scientific concern" that 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  exists. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 To be sure, a significant majority of Republican lawmakers appear to deny a connection between human activity and 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , as demonstrated by the clips in the video.  So initially we were tempted to conclude that this claim did not quite rise to Four Pinocchios. But the video seriously undercuts its credibility by claiming all 240 lawmakers dispute even the very idea of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  - and such gamesmanship with congressional votes is simply not acceptable.
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb240\qj\partightenfactor0

