\f2\b\fs20 \cf0 The complex connection between 
\f1\i \ul climate change
\f2\i0 \ulnone  and Superstorm Sandy
\f0\b0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb200\qj\partightenfactor0

\f3\fs20 \cf0 When it comes to 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  and its effect on Superstorm Sandy, it seems that the loudest voices fall into two camps:
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 l The all-in camp: 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is making the weather more extreme. Sandy is the poster child for that and a sign of things to come.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 l The no-effect camp: 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  played no role in Sandy, and there's no cause for concern about the future.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The inconvenient truth falls in the middle. Considering hurricane history, a careful read of peer-reviewed literature on hurricanes and 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , and the views of a range of scientists, the following five ideas best capture current understanding of the role of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  on Superstorm Sandy:
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb200\qj\partightenfactor0

\f1\i\b\fs20 \cf0 \ul \ulc0 Climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  did not cause Sandy. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f1\i\b\fs20 \ul Climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  does not cause storms; storms form when certain weather ingredients come together. History shows that violent storms have struck the Northeast repeatedly. 
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb200\qj\partightenfactor0

\f3\fs20 \cf0 In the tropics, the formation of hurricanes requires rising air (from converging winds), heat and moisture. These ingredients led to the genesis of Sandy just as they have led to the formation of many storms in the tropics year after year.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In the 1950s, several hurricanes made landfall along the Mid-Atlantic and Northeast coast. Hazel, which made landfall in the Carolinas as a Category 4 hurricane, was arguably more intense than Sandy, producing wind gusts of more than 90 mph from South Carolina to New York state.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 What made Sandy unusual was its interaction with an extratropical low pressure system along the East Coast and its transformation into a "hybrid" storm. But Martin Hoerling, a NOAA meteorologist, disputes the idea that 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  had anything to do with this. "In this case, the immediate cause is most likely little more that the coincidental alignment of a tropical storm with an extratropical storm," he told the New York Times.
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb200\qj\partightenfactor0

\f1\i\b\fs20 \cf0 \ul \ulc0 Climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  may have injected Sandy with more energy and power.
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb200\qj\partightenfactor0

\f3\fs20 \cf0 It's well established that, all other things being equal, warm ocean water energizes hurricanes. The warmer the water, the more intense a hurricane can become. According to Texas Tech atmospheric science professor Katherine Hayhoe, elevated ocean temperatures in the Atlantic might have given Sandy some extra fuel. "October surface ocean temperatures have warmed by two degrees over the last hundred years," Hayhoe told NPR. "So when any given hurricane comes along, on average there's warmer water than there would have been otherwise," she noted, "which gives it more energy, and gives it more strength."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Sea-level rise from man-made 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  increased the water level along the Northeast coast.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Sea levels have risen around 10 to 15 inches over the last 100 years along the East Coast. About half of that rise is from natural causes (sinking land); the other half can be reasonably attributed to man-made warming. So, one could say 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  added six to eight inches to Sandy's storm surge, worsening flooding.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Still, there's little agreement on the significance of this additional water. Chip Knappenburger, a climatologist affiliated with the Cato Institute, has said that "the overwhelming majority of the damage done by the storm surge would have happened anyway."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Chris Mooney, author of "The Republican War on Science," said that the extra water "matters a lot," and pointed to 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  scientist Scott Mandia's estimate that 6,000 more people were impacted for each additional inch of sea-level rise.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Sea levels are projected to continue rising as the Earth warms, raising the maximum water level when hurricanes come ashore and the potential for flooding.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Decreased Arctic sea ice from 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  may have altered steering currents, helping to push Sandy ashore.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 This idea is controversial. As Sandy paralleled the Mid-Atlantic coast, well offshore, it suddenly ran into a roadblock - a strong high pressure system in the North Atlantic - and made a sharp left toward the New Jersey shore. Some researchers speculate that the strength of this roadblock was a consequence of record-low Arctic sea ice, which is linked to 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone .
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The theory goes like this: Less Arctic sea ice reduces temperature contrasts at high latitudes and the strength of westerly winds that serve as the atmosphere's steering current. As a result, the atmosphere's flow slows down and bigger blocks develop.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Rutgers University 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  researcher Jennifer Francis, who has published research supporting this theory, told New Jersey's Star-Ledger that she "absolutely" thinks Arctic sea ice played a role in Sandy's track. "The block was what scared [Sandy] into the west," Francis said. "It's a very, very unusual pattern for a hurricane to take."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But some prominent 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  scientists are skeptical about this theory. "I don't believe it," University Center for Atmospheric Research scientist Kevin Trenberth told the New York Times. The "null hypothesis has to be that this is just 'weather' and natural variability," he said.
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb200\qj\partightenfactor0

\f1\i\b\fs20 \cf0 \ul \ulc0 Climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is likely to slowly increase the intensity of hurricanes in the future.
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb200\qj\partightenfactor0

\f3\fs20 \cf0 After a hurricane, you often hear experts say something to the effect of "
\f1\i\b \ul Climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is increasing the odds of these kinds of events." It's not that simple.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Yes, scientists project gradual increases in hurricane intensity, with heavier rainfall and stronger peak winds. But with the exception of the most intense storms, hurricane frequency is projected to decline.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 A clear human influence on hurricane activity may take decades to reveal itself. Although observed warming may be infusing storms with more power, it remains a challenge to quantify the human connection. NOAA hurricane and 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  researcher Tom Knutson put it this way: "It is premature to conclude that human activities - and particularly greenhouse gas emissions that cause global warming - have already had a detectable impact on Atlantic hurricane activity."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In a commentary in Foreign Policy magazine, MIT professor of atmospheric science Kerry Emanuel stresses that establishing a causal connection between 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  and storms such as Sandy is not needed as a basis for action. The risks inherent in toying with the atmosphere and the possible consequences, Emanuel says, are reason enough to stop "keep kicking the 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  can down the road."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "[T]he argument that there is no risk or that we should do nothing is both scientifically and morally indefensible," Emanuel writes.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Indeed, there is a great deal of evidence that man-made 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is real and poses risks to society and the environment, especially if its pace accelerates. Stronger hurricanes are just one of many possible unwelcome consequences. There's really no need to oversell connections between storms such as Sandy and global warming to build a case for responding to these risks.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 - Jason Samenow
