\f3\fs20 \cf0 The Trump administration is so fearful of acknowledging 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  that White House negotiators are trying to erase all mention of it and the Paris agreement from a multinational statement about the Arctic region, The Post reported last week.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In doing so, the Trump administration has demonstrated its cowardly denial that the region is warming two to three times faster than the rest of the planet, putting its own people in harm's way and damaging relations with allies around the world.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 This isn't the first time this episode has played out. I bore witness to the administration's self-inflicted embarrassment two years ago while working at the Interior Department. Then, as now, the leader of the free world stood diminished while other nations and the people most affected by the 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  crisis faced the consequences.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The eight nations of the Arctic Council, established in 1996, take turns chairing the multinational forum. Every two years, as leadership 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , foreign ministers must sign a negotiated ministerial declaration reaffirming the work and ambitions of the council. Since Trump has entered office, that has meant Arctic nations must suffer through absurd negotiations with 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  deniers in the White House.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 I was involved in those negotiations two years ago, at the conclusion of the U.S. chairmanship of the council. During the U.S. term, the council was laser-focused on 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  and prepared to deliver a menu of responses. For example, we had developed, with an international team, a 
\f1\i\b \ul climate-change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  adaptation and resilience strategy that was up for approval by the foreign ministers.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 It was not a controversial measure. But because U.S. leadership of the council concluded five months into the Trump administration, I was one of the many career civil servants attempting to explain to White House staff why 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  measures should be approved at all. Trump loyalists with no background in science, the Arctic or diplomacy scrutinized every word of the nonbinding declaration, looking for 
\f1\i\b \ul climate-change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  language to delete.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 It didn't end there. Once negotiators finalized the declaration, another wave of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate-change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  insecurity beset the martinets at the White House, and they told then-Secretary of State Rex Tillerson to demand additional 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  just days before the signing ceremony in Fairbanks, Alaska. Those 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone ? Eliminating or 
\f1\i\b \ul changing
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  language about - you guessed it - 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  and the Paris agreement.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 For a multinational consensus body focused on sustainability and the environment, this was unheard of. Career diplomats at the State Department scrambled, apologetically, to gain approval from their foreign colleagues. Tempers flared and senior diplomats from Canada, Nordic countries and even Russia privately expressed disgust.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 It was also an insult to the people of the Arctic. In addition to the eight member nations, six indigenous organizations sit at the Arctic Council table, representing hundreds of thousands of people whose ancestors have lived in the Arctic for thousands of years. Unique among multinational bodies, this direct role gives a voice to indigenous knowledge and priorities.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The indigenous peoples of the Arctic live squarely in the path of dramatic 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  impacts. Vulnerable coastal villages in Alaska face the twin threats of vicious storms and coastal erosion as protective sea ice shrinks and permafrost thaws beneath their feet. Subsistence hunters in some areas can no longer safely travel and hunt on sea ice.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 These people are not running from the threat. They are planning village relocations, using smartphone apps to record environmental 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  and find reliable ice routes, testing renewable energy systems and exploring technological fixes to food and water security issues. They have shown the world what it looks like to rise up and adapt.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The Trump administration, however, doesn't seem to care. In attempting to erase mention of the threat, they are erasing the lives at stake.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Soon after the Arctic Council dust-up, the administration reassigned me to an auditing job in an office that collects royalty income from fossil fuel companies. Before resigning my position, I filed a whistleblower complaint in July 2017 alleging that the Trump administration retaliated against me for speaking out about the dangers of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  among Alaskan native communities. This new round of international censorship and science denial only confirms that they still have their heads deep in the oil-stained sands of their fossil-fuel-industry donors.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 It comforts me to know that the tenacity and ambition of the people of the Arctic endure despite a president who cannot see beyond industry-funded 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  disinformation. Even still, they must wonder: How much longer must we wait before we no longer suffer such cowardly denial from our leaders? How long must we stand alone?
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Joel Clement, director of the Office of Policy Analysis at the Interior Department from 2011 to 2017, is a senior fellow at both the Harvard Belfer Center Arctic Initiative and the Union of Concerned Scientists Center for Science and Democracy.
