\f3\fs20 \cf0 George F. Will once again ignored scientific evidence when he claimed that there has been no global warming over the past decade ["
\f1\i\b \ul Climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  Fixers' Hard Sell," 
\f4\i \cf2 \ul \ulc2 op-ed
\f3\i0 \cf0 \ulnone , July 23].
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb200\qj\partightenfactor0

\f3\fs20 \cf0 Earth's average temperature rises and falls in large part because of multiyear ocean cycles, such as El Ni\'c3\'b1o and La Ni\'c3\'b1a. At the same time, human-induced global warming has been steadily pushing average temperatures higher. Because of the natural ocean cycles, 1998 was a warm year. Global warming made it even hotter. Conversely, 2008 was a cooler year, but global warming made it less cool.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 That said, there are plenty of obvious signs of global warming over the past decade, including shrinking Arctic summer sea ice. In 2007, the region's sea ice was at an all-time low since satellite observations began. Last year marked the second-lowest year.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 All corners of America are already experiencing the effects of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone . Mr. Will should take a look at the federal government's recent report "Global 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate Change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  Impacts in the United States" to find out the facts.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 BRENDA EKWURZEL
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Washington
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The writer is a 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  scientist with the Union of Concerned Scientists.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 --
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 George F. Will couldn't be further off base with his continually baffling approach to 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone . Should we expect to see a piece from him this week arguing that Earth is flat?
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 First and foremost, development need not be sacrificed in the name of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone . In 2008, the World Bank's Independent Evaluation Group found that there is no significant trade-off between 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  mitigation and energy access for the world's poorest. The provision of basic electricity services for the world's unconnected households would add only a third of one percentage point to global greenhouse gas emissions!
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The argument for renewable energy is not an attack on economic growth; it's a plea for responsible and sustainable development.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 As for the "no one else cares about 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  so why should we" case, the United States  has an important role to play as a leader -- the last eight years of stalled 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  negotiations are the result of an administration that refused to play the part.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Furthermore, as a World Bank donor country, the United States is able to push the bank to allocate its sizable resources to renewables in place of coal.
\f0\fs24 \

