\f3\fs20 \cf0 Traffic to federal websites soars under new administration
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The events of the past week were worrying to advocates of government action on 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , with the removal of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  priorities from the White House website and the order to freeze all Environmental Protection Agency contracts following the inauguration of a president who has said he is "not a big believer" in the fact that humans have played a role in 
\f1\i\b \ul changing
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  Earth's 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone .
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But these events have also been very good for website traffic.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 According to data from analytics.usa.gov, which tracks Web traffic on all dot-gov websites, several pages related to 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  have been extremely popular in the week since President Trump's inauguration.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 On Friday, a National Park Service report about the agency's "Cultural Resources 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate Change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  Strategy" was the most downloaded document from a government website. Thousands more people wanted to download that document than those who downloaded the form to apply for passport renewal or any of the Internal Revenue Service documents required to file tax returns.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In the spring, Jonathan Jarvis, who was then the Park Service's director, spoke with The Washington Post about the 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  threat to parks. "A lot of our big, national parks are in extreme environments - high elevation, desert, Alaska, coastline," he said. "These are the places that we're already seeing the effects of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , and they're going to be accelerated in these environments, with sea level rise, storm surge, thermokarsting" - when permafrost thaws - "in the Arctic, fires in the Sierra, drought all over. It's going to upset the paradigm upon which we've been managing for 100 years. That's going to be a big challenge, and, frankly, we haven't figured it out."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  strategy report outlines how the Park Service aims to address the effects of 
\f1\i\b \ul changing
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  conditions on archaeological sites, historic buildings, museum collections, sacred landscapes and other cultural resources. It was downloaded 29,583 times Thursday.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Over at EPA.gov, nine of the top-10 downloads were related to 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone . On Thursday alone, 3,036 people downloaded the agency's 2016 report on 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  indicators, which lists evidence for global warming and provides ways to track its effects on the planet.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 An EPA contractor, who spoke on the condition of anonymity because the worker was not authorized to discuss the matter, said the page  EPA.gov/climatechange  had a 2,700 percent increase in visitors in the first five days after the inauguration, as compared with the five days before. The agency's 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  research page had a 500 percent increase in visitors.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The Trump administration had planned to scrub these 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  pages from the EPA's website, an EPA employee told The Post. But career staffers pushed back against the plan, and the political appointees overseeing the agency backed away from it.
