\f3\fs20 \cf0 Though inundated by news of the three-day government shutdown and an allegation that   President Trump had an affair with an adult-film star, an announcement late last week from federal scientists should, in the long term, prove far more consequential.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 2017 was the second-hottest year in 138 years of record-keeping, trailing only 2016.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "The planet is warming remarkably uniformly," Gavin Schmidt, director of the Goddard Institute for Space Studies in New York, told The Post's Chris Mooney and other reporters Thursday.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The measurements were made by NASA, better known for rocketing astronauts into orbit than for tabulating rising global temperatures. Yet the space agency - one of the few government agencies beloved by Republicans and Democrats alike - does both.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 NASA is uncommonly popular for an arm of the federal government. More than two-thirds of U.S. adults view the space agency favorably, according to a 2015 Pew survey. Unlike so many other topics in politics, NASA's sky-high popularity bridges the interplanetary void that often separates partisans on policy issues. Majorities of independents (70 percent), Democrats (68 percent) and Republicans (63 percent) say they like the space agency.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 That fondness - born out of completing daring missions, such as sending men to the moon and robots to Mars - appears to translate into trust. Of 11 government agencies that study 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  - including the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention and the Smithsonian Institution - NASA is thought by Americans to have the most talented researchers, according to a 2012 study. Sixty percent of respondents rated NASA research scientists as "very competent" - higher than any other government agency surveyed in that study.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But the love for NASA doesn't mean the GOP embraces the agency's stance on 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  science. Last year, only 18 percent of Republicans said they worried a great deal about 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , according to Gallup.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The incongruity between support for the space agency and its 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  warnings stems from a "crucial tension in conservative attitudes towards 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone ," according to John Cook, a research assistant professor at the Center for 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate Change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  Communication at George Mason University.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "On the one hand, there is respect for scientific institutions like NASA," Cook wrote by email. "On the other hand, acceptance of human-caused global warming is low."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Part of the disconnect probably comes from the fact that the public probably doesn't understand the full scope of the space agency's mission.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Yes, NASA sends robotic spacecrafts to explore our solar system's other planets and sends telescopes into orbit to observe distant galaxies. But the original 1958 law that created NASA also directs the agency to expand "human knowledge of phenomena in the atmosphere" right here on Earth - an objective its 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  lab in New York carries out by calculating the atmospheric phenomenon of rising global temperatures.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Nevertheless, the image of NASA as solely a builder and launcher of rockets persists. In the 2012 study, 41 percent of respondents, a plurality, said they did not know how much 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  research NASA conducted.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Americans are more likely to think such work was carried out by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration or the Environmental Protection Agency. (NOAA, using different methodology, concluded that last year was the third-warmest ever recorded.)
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In truth, no agency spends more on 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  science than NASA, according to the Government Accountability Office.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 More broadly, there's significant skepticism, especially among Republicans, about the scientific consensus inside and outside of NASA that the burning of fossil fuels and other human activity is warming the atmosphere.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "A short answer is that most Republicans don't know about the scientific consensus," said Anthony Leiserowitz, a Yale research scientist and director of the Yale Program on 
\f1\i\b \ul Climate Change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  Communication who conducted the 2012 survey on NASA.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But when survey takers are told about that consensus - by one 2013 count, 97 percent of scientific studies agree on man-made global warming - "people then update their other beliefs about global warming being real and worrisome," said Edward Maibach, a George Mason professor who worked with Leiserowitz on the NASA survey.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In their published papers, Maibach and Leiserowitz dubbed knowing the scientific consensus on 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  a "gateway belief."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Their research shows that people generally take their cues from politicians rather than 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  scientists when it comes to the issue, which means for Republicans, they are hearing a lot of doubt about 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  science.       
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "One of the simple, clear ideas about global warming that they have heard over and over and over again, because it is the product of a strategic communication campaign," Maibach said, "is that there is a lot of disagreement among the experts."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 With Trump, these barbs are even sharper. On Twitter, he has called those concerned about 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  "hoaxsters,"              "con artists" and "dollar sucking wiseguys."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But other Republicans' rhetoric, even if more tempered, has taken on NASA more directly. When NASA and NOAA announced 2015 was a (then) record-setting year for global temperatures, the office of Sen. Ted Cruz (R-Tex.) said that "satellite and weather balloon data do not show 2015 as a record year."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 On the other side of the Capitol, House Science Committee Chairman Rep. Lamar Smith (R-Tex.), who chairs the House Science, Space and Technology Committee, called last year for a "rebalancing" of NASA's budget toward more space exploration and away from earth science.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Indeed, NASA's Earth Science Division has seen its budget oscillate between presidential administrations, with President George W. Bush reducing resources and his successor, Barack Obama, restoring them.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "Scientists are trained to basically say it once and move on to the newest thing," Maibach said. "Scientists don't like to go back and repeat themselves over and over and over again, because that's just not the way science works. But that's the way public understanding is built. And politicians know that."
\f0\fs24 \
