\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone .
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Still, the teens have won the backing of many leading environmental groups, including Greenpeace, the Sunrise Movement and 350.org. This month, more than 250 scientists released a letter of support for the school strikes. 
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In Europe, where the 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  strikes have been filling plazas in capital cities for months, leaders such as German Chancellor Angela Merkel have endorsed the movement.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But other politicians have mocked it. Christian Lindner, leader of a pro-business party in Germany, urged students to stay in school, saying that "politics is for professionals."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 In Washington on Friday, the young people gathered on Capitol Hill had a message for the politicians inside: Get moving.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Standing toward the back of the crowd, 16-year-old Jerome Nkugwa spoke about how the impacts of 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  are expected to grow more severe over time. He nodded toward the Capitol.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "Something worse is coming," said Nkugwa. "We came out to remind them to do something about it."
