\f3\fs20 \cf0 What happened to "
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone " and "global warming"?
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The Earth is still getting hotter, but those terms have nearly disappeared from political vocabulary. Instead, they have been replaced by less charged and more consumer-friendly expressions for the warming planet.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 President Obama's State of the Union address Tuesday\'e2\'88\'9a was a prime time example of this shift. The president said mentioned"
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone " just once\'e2\'88\'9a - compared with zero mentions in the 2011 address and two in 2010. When he did utter the phrase, it was he did so merely to acknowledge the polarized atmosphere 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  in Washington, saying, \'e2\'88\'9a. The president said: "The differences difference in this chamber may be too deep right now to pass a comprehensive plan to fight 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone .\'e2\'88\'9a" By contrast, Obama used the terms "energy" and "clean energy" nearly two dozen times.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 That tally reflects a broader 
\f1\i\b \ul change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  in how the president talks about the planet. 
\f4\i \cf2 \ul \ulc2 A recent Brown University study
\f3\i0 \cf0 \ulnone looked specifically at the Obama administration's language and found that mentions of "
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone " have been replaced by calls for "clean energy" and "energy independence." Graciela Kincaid, a co-author of the study, wrote: "The phrases '
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone ' and 'global warming' have become all but taboo on Capitol Hill. These terms are stunningly absent from the political arena."
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb240\qj\partightenfactor0

\f3\fs20 \cf0 In 2009, the Obama administration purposefully began to refer to greenhouse gas emissions as "carbon pollution" and "heat-trapping emissions." This 
\f1\i\b \ul change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is evident in statements from top officials such as White House science adviser John Holdren, Energy Secretary Steven Chu, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration head Jane Lubchenco and Environmental Protection Agency Administrator Lisa Jackson. Lubchenco 
\f4\i \cf2 \ul \ulc2 told a reporter
\f3\i0 \cf0 \ulnone  that the choice of those terms "is intended to make what's happening more understandable and more accessible to non-technical audiences."
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb200\qj\partightenfactor0

\f3\fs20 \cf0 These choices are also reflected in news coverage around the world. My colleague Maria Mansfield and I 
\f4\i \cf2 \ul \ulc2 monitor 50 major newspapers
\f3\i0 \cf0 \ulnone in 20 countries, and we documented that explicit mentions of "
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone " and "global warming" dropped by more than a third from 2010 to 2011.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 There is power in how language is deployed, and people setting policy agendas know this well. In 2002, Republican political strategist Frank Luntz issued a widely cited memo advising that the Bush administration should shift its rhetoric on the 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone . "It's time for us to start talking about '
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone ' instead of global warming. . . . '
\f1\i\b \ul Climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone ' is less frightening than 'global warming,' " the memo said.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Luntz was not alone in wanting to 
\f1\i\b \ul change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  the terminology. The nonprofit group EcoAmerica issued a report in 2009 arguing that the terms "global warming" and "
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone " both needed rebranding. In their place, the group recommended the phrase "our deteriorating atmosphere."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 But what do we lose when global warming and 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  get repackaged as clean energy? We wind up missing a thorough understanding of the breadth of the problem and the range of possible solutions.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 To start, talking only about clean energy omits critical biological and physical factors that contribute to the warming  
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone . "Clean energy" doesn't call to mind the ways we use the land and how the environment is 
\f1\i\b \ul changing
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone . Where in the term is the notion of the 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  pollution that results from clear-cutting Amazon rain forests? What about methane release in the Arctic, where global warming is exposing new areas of soil in the permafrost?
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "Clean energy" also neatly bypasses any idea that we might need to curb our consumption. If the energy is clean, after all, why worry about how much we're using - or how unequal the access to energy sources might be?
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 And terms such as "carbon pollution" ignore that 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  isn't just a carbon issue. Some greenhouse gases, such as nitrous oxide, do not contain carbon, and not all carbon-containing emissions, such as carbon monoxide, trap heat.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 When the president moves away from talking about 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  and talks more generally about energy, as he did in the State of the Union, calling for "an all-out, all-of-the-above strategy that develops every available source of American energy," the impact is more than just political.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Calling 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  by another name creates limits of its own. The way we talk about the problem affects how we deal with it. And though some new wording may deflect political heat, it can't alter the fact that, "
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone " or not, the 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is 
\f1\i\b \ul changing
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone .
\f0\fs24 \
