\f3\fs20 \cf0 To a psychologist, 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  looks as if it was designed to be ignored.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 It is a global problem, with no obvious villains and no one-step solutions, whose worst effects seem as if they'll befall somebody else at some other time. In short, if someone set out to draw up a problem that people would not care about, one expert on human behavior said, it would look exactly like 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone .
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 That's the upshot of a spate of new research that tries to explain stalled U.S. efforts to combat greenhouse-gas emissions by putting the country on the couch.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Polls -- including one last month -- indicate that a sizable, though shrinking, number of Americans believe 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is happening. Most of those people think it is a "serious" problem. So, rationally, shouldn't they be doing more to fight it?
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The problem, many psychologists say, is the "rationally."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Those who are concerned that a real problem is being left unaddressed have called for a 
\f1\i\b \ul change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  in the way that green groups talk about 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , which has traditionally been heavy on warnings about drought and stranded polar bears. Instead, researchers suggested a new set of back-door appeals, designed essentially to fool people into serving their own -- and the planet's -- best interests.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "We are collectively irrational, in the sense that we should really care about the long-term well-being of the planet but when we get up in the morning it's very hard to motivate ourselves," said Dan Ariely, a professor of behavioral economics at Duke University, who gave a keynote speech   last month at a Washington conference devoted to understanding why people don't do more to save energy.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Psychologists studying the issue say that the now-familiar warnings about 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  kick at emotional dead spots in all human brains -- but especially in American brains. Researchers have only theories to explain why people in the United States have done less than those in such places as Europe and Japan. Some think Americans are culturally leery of programs the government might develop to target 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , trusting instead that the free market will solve major problems.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 One U.S. researcher thought television is to blame: All those TV ads have made Americans more focused on their own wants, she theorized, and less likely to care about the long-term good.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 No matter where the public's complacency springs from, psychologists have seen this kind of thing before, Ariely said: "That's why we don't exercise, and we overeat, and we bite our fingernails. . . . It's not something where we're going to overcome human nature."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Last month, shortly before Monday's start of an international conference on 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone , the United States and China made pledges to work on cutting greenhouse-gas emissions. But even these underscored the point that much more remains to be done: The United States offered to cut emissions less than environmentalists say it needs to; China offered to cut in ways it was planning to anyway.
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs20 \cf0 Obstacles to progress 
\f0\b0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb200\qj\partightenfactor0

\f3\fs20 \cf0 The obstacles to progress -- internationally and in the U.S. Senate, where a 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  bill is stalled -- aren't just mental.
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb200\qj\partightenfactor0

\f1\i\b\fs20 \cf0 \ul \ulc0 Climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is a policy problem that has "psychological distance": In layman's terms, there's a sense that this is a problem for somebody else or some other time.
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb200\qj\partightenfactor0

\f3\fs20 \cf0 Although researchers say the 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is, in fact, already shifting, psychologists say many Americans still don't feel close to the issue. And though scientists say that 
\f1\i\b \ul change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is unequivocal, the science can be confusing: It is complex, and vocal skeptics are still saying the evidence is not at all conclusive.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Another problem with 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  is called, more obscurely, "system justification." This refers to humankind's deep-seated love for the status quo and willingness to defend it.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 This is why 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  isn't like the hole in the ozone layer: In that crisis, the solution was to substitute new chemicals for old ones, and the 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  happened mainly inside refrigerator coils and spray cans. In this one, they could alter basic things about modern life, everything from light bulbs to cars to air travel.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 A third problem is that psychologists say humans can fret about only so many things at once -- the technical term is the "finite pool of worry."
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The proof of that might be found in last month's Washington Post-ABC News poll, which showed that belief in 
\f1\i\b \ul climate change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  had actually fallen 13 percentage points since 2006, from 85 percent to 72. It could be that new worries such as lost jobs and swine flu crowded old ones out of the pool.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Psychological researchers say one possible way to overcome all these obstacles is to frame the 
\f1\i\b \ul changes
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  needed to curb carbon emissions as "saving" the American way of life, instead of 
\f1\i\b \ul changing
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  it. Another is to pair warnings about the 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  with concrete suggestions about what to do, so people can act instead of just stewing in worry.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 Another is to tap into two powerful human impulses: to be like one's neighbors and then to beat them at something.
\f0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs20 \cf0 Call in the elephants 
\f0\b0\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl260\sb200\qj\partightenfactor0

\f3\fs20 \cf0 In one small study around San Diego in 2007, researchers hung four fliers on doorknobs. One told homeowners that they should conserve energy because it helped the environment. One said saving energy was socially responsible. One said that it saved money. The fourth said that the majority of neighbors in the community were doing it.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 The researchers waited and then read the meters. The houses with the fourth flier showed the most 
\f1\i\b \ul change
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone .
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 "Simply urging people -- or telling them that it's a good idea to recycle or conserve energy -- is the same as nothing," said Robert Cialdini, a professor at Arizona State University who worked on the study.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 One of those listening to the psychologists is Rep. Brian Baird (D-Wash.), who introduced a bill calling on the Department of Energy to study "social and behavioral factors" that affect energy use. It passed a House committee, though Baird said some Republicans called it "mind control." "These [ideas] can all be met with derision until you try it," Baird said.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 For now, however, some psychologists say they're frustrated that their ideas seem to have been picked up only unevenly by environmental groups.
\f0\fs24 \

\f3\fs20 For instance, an ad 
\f4\i \cf2 \ul \ulc2 campaign
\f3\i0 \cf0 \ulnone  running in the United States and 34 other countries calls for progress at international 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
\f3\i0\b0 \ulnone  talks in Copenhagen using a play on the city's name: It becomes "Hopenhagen." The ads' strategy was devised by the firm Ogilvy & Mather, where an executive said they, also, wanted to leave behind gloomy messages about the 
\f1\i\b \ul climate
